article.description: Antawn Jamison had 35 points and 16 rebounds to lead the Wizards to a 119-114 victory over the Bobcats.
article.headline: One night after beating Pistons, Wizards slip past Bobcats
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Playing in front of his mother, father and 18 other friends and family members, Antawn Jamison had one of his best games of the season. Jamison, who grew up in Charlotte, tied his season high with 35 points and 16 rebounds to lead the Washington Wizards to a 119-114 victory over the Bobcats on Tuesday night. "It's always good to have my family and friends come see me play," said Jamison, who said he last had his parents in the crowd Dec. 26 when the Los Angeles Lakers played at Washington. Gilbert Arenas scored 34 points and Caron Butler added 25 to join Jamison as the only productive Wizards players. "Those three guys are pretty good," Bobcats coach Bernie Bickerstaff said. "When you've got three guys who can score, you can put the ball in their hands." The Wizards weren't exactly clicking on all cylinders -- the rest of the team combined for just 25 points, and the bench didn't contribute until the fourth quarter -- but it was still enough as they won two straight over two very different opponents. "Let's face it -- when myself, Gilbert and Caron step up, we play a lot better as a team," Jamison said. Washington was coming off a victory over the Detroit Pistons, the best team in the NBA, then had to claw one out against the Bobcats, one of the worst teams in the league. Washington opened several double-digit leads, only to allow Charlotte to chip away and pull into contention -- something the Wizards expected to happen. "No one has ever really put them away," Arenas said. "You can't put them away. They play too hard." Charlotte made its final run with 2:05 to play when Jumaine Jones scored to cut the Wizards' lead to 110-108. But Arenas scored on a driving layup on the next possession and was fouled by Jones. Arenas made the free throw to push it to 113-108. Bernard Robinson made a pair of free throws for Charlotte to cut it to three, but Arenas scored on another drive. Kareem Rush hit a short jumper to cut it to 115-112 with 54 seconds to play, but it was the closest the Bobcats would get as the game quickly slipped away. Jones fouled out on Charlotte's next possession when he fouled Antonio Daniels in a scramble for a loose ball. Daniels made both free throws, then was fouled seconds later by Gerald Wallace. It was Wallace's sixth foul and infuriated Bickerstaff, who deliberately told Raymond Felton to take his time checking in because, "I want to make them wait." Felton eventually made his way onto the court, Daniels made both free throws and Bickerstaff threw his hands up in disgust and told the Bobcats not to foul anymore. Jones scored 18 to lead a balanced attack for the Bobcats, who had seven players in double figures. Felton had 17 despite missing most of the fourth quarter while he had his face examined after taking a hard elbow from Etan Thomas. Wallace finished with 15, Brevin Knight had 13, Matt Carroll scored 11, and Primoz Brezec and Melvin Ely each had 10.

Game notes
The Bobcats announced before the game forward Emeka Okafor will not play again this season. He has missed 37 games with a sprained right ankle that has now developed severe tendinitis. ... But the news wasn't all bad for Charlotte -- forward Sean May is scheduled to meet with the medical staff on Thursday to see if his surgically repaired knee has healed enough to let him play again this season. ... Jamison's career high is 51 points, done twice. ... Awvee Storey's 11-foot jumper with 11:39 to play was Washington's first bench points of the game.
